      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Creating a Home Office on a Budget: Full Setup for Under $300</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">A proper ergonomic home office does not need to cost thousands. Here is exactly what to buy for a complete setup — with an ergonomic chair, proper desk, external monitor, and good lighting — all under $300.</p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">
        <div class="rounded-2xl bg-accent-50 border border-accent-200 p-6 not-prose">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent-800">The Goal</p>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-accent-700">Build a comfortable, ergonomically sound home office that supports 6+ hours of daily work. Every item chosen balances price, quality, and long-term usability. These are not disposable picks — each piece can serve as a foundation you upgrade around over time.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>The Complete Shopping List</h2>

        <h3>1. Desk: IKEA Lagkapten / Adils Combo — $55</h3>
        <p>55" wide, 23" deep. Clean white or wood-look laminate surface. Simple screw-in legs. This is the standard starter desk — not fancy, but functional and surprisingly sturdy for the price. Get the 55" version to have room for a monitor and notebook side by side. Assembly takes about 20 minutes.</p>
        <p><strong>Alternative:</strong> Check Facebook Marketplace or Craigslist for used desks. Office furniture depreciates fast — you can often find a $300+ desk for $50-80 in like-new condition.</p>

        <h3>2. Chair: Hbada Office Task Chair — $130</h3>
        <p>Adjustable lumbar support (the most important ergonomic feature), mesh back for breathability, flip-up armrests, and a comfortable foam seat. This chair consistently tops "best budget ergonomic chair" lists for a reason. It will not last a decade like a Herman Miller, but it provides genuine ergonomic support for 3-5 years.</p>
        <p><strong>Key tip:</strong> Make sure to adjust the lumbar support height to fit your lower back curve. An unadjusted ergonomic chair is not ergonomic.</p>

        <h3>3. Monitor: Dell S2421H 24" IPS — $110</h3>
        <p>24-inch 1080p IPS panel with thin bezels and built-in speakers. IPS means good color accuracy and wide viewing angles. This monitor is bright, sharp, and a massive upgrade from squinting at a laptop screen. Connect via HDMI. The built-in speakers are nothing special but work for video calls.</p>
        <p><strong>Alternative:</strong> Used 24" Dell or HP monitors cost $40-70 on eBay or Facebook Marketplace. Office monitors are reliable and depreciate heavily — buying used is very safe here.</p>

        <h3>4. Lighting: TaoTronics LED Desk Lamp — $30</h3>
        <p>5 brightness levels, 5 color temperature modes (warm to cool), USB charging port built into the base. Flexible neck for positioning. This lamp has over 20,000 positive reviews on Amazon and does everything a good desk lamp should do. The USB port on the base is a nice convenience feature.</p>

        <h3>5. Monitor Riser — $20</h3>
        <p>A simple bamboo or metal monitor stand raises your screen to eye level. This is critical — looking down at a laptop or low monitor is the fastest route to neck pain. If you are on a super tight budget, a stack of books works too (and looks charmingly academic).</p>

        <h2>Total: $345 (Slightly Over — Here Is How to Hit $300)</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Buy the monitor used instead of new: saves $40-60.</li>
          <li>Get a cheaper desk from a thrift store or Facebook Marketplace: saves $20-30.</li>
          <li>Skip the monitor riser and use books temporarily: saves $20.</li>
          <li>With all three adjustments, you are well under $300.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to Upgrade First (When You Have More Budget)</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>The chair.</strong> A $500-800 ergonomic chair is the single best upgrade you can make. See our <a href="/blog/ergonomic-chair-buying-guide/">chair buying guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>A second monitor.</strong> Adding the same Dell S2421H gives you a dual-monitor productivity boost. See our <a href="/blog/monitor-setup-guide/">monitor setup guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>A sit-stand desk.</strong> Moving throughout the day is better than sitting perfectly. The Flexispot EC1 ($250) is the entry point. See our <a href="/blog/standing-desk-guide/">standing desk guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>A monitor arm.</strong> Frees up desk space and gives you perfect monitor positioning.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="rounded-2xl bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 p-6 not-prose mt-10">
